        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down Bromley Kent</placeName>
                    <date>July 7th</date>
                    <salute>My dear Galton</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I return the enclosed signed with very great pleasure.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>Many thanks for information about D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Barths work which I will read.<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>I continue much interested about all domestic animals of all savage nations, though I shall not take up cattle in detail.<ref target="#foot.f4"/> If on reading I sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. have anything to ask I will accept your kind offer &amp; ask.— Anything about savages taking any the least pain in breeding &amp; crossing their domestic animals is of particular interest to me.</p>
<p>With kind remembrances to Mrs Galton,<ref target="#foot.f5"/> pray believe me | Yours very sincerely | Ch. Darwin.</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Dated by the reference to ‘D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Barths work’ (see n. 3, below).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">The item has not been identified, although it may have related to the <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4103.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Royal Geographical Society</ref>, of which <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1797.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Francis Galton</ref> was honorary secretary. Galton had been elected to the position in May 1857. CD had been a fellow since 1838.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">The German geographer and traveller <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_298.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Heinrich Barth</ref>, a member of the British expedition to explore North and Central Africa, 1849–55, returned to England in September 1855 and began writing up an account of his African travels. The first three volumes of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_393.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Barth 1857–8</ref> were published between 15 and 30 May 1857 (<hi rend="italic">Publishers’ Circular</hi>, 1 June 1857, p. 230).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">CD discussed the origins and variations of domestic cattle in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7951.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Variation</hi></ref> 1: 79–93.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1797.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Francis Galton</ref> had married Louisa Jane Butler in 1853.</note>
        </div>        
            
